reviews.review_text: Overlooked Show Another phenomenal matrix of one of the 70's most overlooked years and shows. I don't understand why this show gets such little mention. This is a fantastic matrix of one of the Dead's jazziest shows. Not only that, but you get the rarity of a performance of Blues For Allah, a real highlight. The real stand out I think is Peggy O. I have never heard another version played quite like this one. King Solomon's Marbles is also a rare gem played to perfection here out of Blues For Allah into space and back into Blues For Allah. Thank you to all those involved in putting out this gem of a show.

truly is a gem show+Matrix Not going to get redundant , skydog says it all. Great show and setlist. Love the 75 sound on tunes like Big River and Me and My Uncle.

thank you for this one

Pure '75 bliss... While I fully admire and love the Rob Bertrando AUD recording of this show, I would have to say I prefer this Matrix over the AUD. This Matrix is also superior to the other one listed and contains the full show. A top notch job was done here balancing out the booming AUD sound with the rather flat SBD recording. The finished product is a delightful slice of pure, acidic dead. This performance is one of my favorites, containing the best version of Crazy Fingers I have ever heard. The Franklin's Tower tempo is slower than the later versions enabling Phil to do similar bass work as he did on the album. Keith does some really great Fender Rhodes piano work; he is my favorite Rhodes pianist. A new spin on an already awesome show! Enjoy!

firsts the lost year of 75, first crazy, help and franklin here

peggy-o unlike any other, such a slow pace its nice

very jammy second set is good stuff
winterland 75' Sweet peggy-o,real nice help>slipknot>franklin.set 2 is brilliant.

Fennario Oh this is hot! (A little slow out of the gate.)
Crazy Fingers never easy to land for Garcia but so much cool imagery plus a good space for Jerry to jam out.
Peggy-O is mellow!(The Vibe flows from here)
Help > Slip (just a brief second where I am feeling a Dark Star-how cool would that be
Help>Slip>Dark Star!)
Also really like the Franklin's.(good jam)
Not meaning to short change Bob's contribution to these sets but if ever there is a Jerry centered year 1975 is it.(and most years after)
To be fair to Weir there are not many musicians who could go one for one with Garcia on a nightly basis. (Pigpen has departed and Phil has stopped singing leads)
Wonder why the 2nd set is so short time wise?
but the whole Blues for Allah got pretty intense.
Superb recording-it really makes a difference.
Sometimes Blues For Allah reminds me of the movie 'Spinal Tap' just in the intro but the jams are not for the faint of heart.
Jerry Garcia and Friends Definitely one of my top ten live in person GD shows ever. Billed as Jerry Garcia and Friends during the GDs retirement period.
